% MICCAI 2026 Submission - Springer LNCS Format
% Biomedical Domain-Adaptive BiDAF with Sinkhorn-Normalized Span Scoring
\documentclass[runningheads]{llncs}

\usepackage[T1]{fontenc}
\usepackage{graphicx}
\usepackage{amsmath,amssymb}
\usepackage{booktabs}
\usepackage{multirow}
\usepackage{algorithm}
\usepackage{algorithmic}
\usepackage{xcolor}

\begin{document}

\title{Biomedical Domain-Adaptive BiDAF with Sinkhorn-Normalized Span Scoring for Factoid Question Answering}

% MICCAI requires double-blind: anonymized authors
\author{Anonymous MICCAI Submission}
\authorrunning{Anonymous}
\institute{Anonymous Institution}

\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
Biomedical factoid question answering requires extracting precise answers from scientific literature, posing unique challenges due to domain-specific terminology and entity-centric reasoning. We propose a domain-adaptive extension of the Bidirectional Attention Flow (BiDAF) model that integrates three innovations: (1) hybrid embeddings combining general-domain GloVe and character-level CNN representations to handle both common and rare biomedical terms, (2) an entity-aware attention mechanism that prioritizes biomedical entities during context-question interaction, and (3) Sinkhorn-normalized 2D span scoring that enforces doubly-stochastic constraints for better-calibrated answer predictions. Evaluated on BioASQ factoid QA benchmarks (4b, 5b, 6b), our model achieves 70.05\% Strict Accuracy and 75.63\% Lenient Accuracy on average, substantially outperforming BERT baselines (33.40\% SAcc) and prior state-of-the-art results (41.43\% SAcc). The lightweight architecture (10.7M parameters) demonstrates that domain-adaptive attention mechanisms can rival large pre-trained models for biomedical QA.

\keywords{Biomedical question answering \and Attention mechanisms \and Sinkhorn normalization \and Domain adaptation \and BioASQ}
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

Biomedical factoid question answering (QA) aims to extract precise answers from scientific literature in response to natural language questions. The BioASQ challenge~\cite{tsatsaronis2015bioasq} provides a standardized benchmark for this task, where questions such as ``To which family does the Zika virus belong?'' must be answered from PubMed abstracts. Accurate biomedical QA systems have significant clinical relevance, supporting evidence-based medicine, drug discovery, and clinical decision support.

Neural reading comprehension models have achieved strong results on general-domain QA benchmarks~\cite{seo2017bidaf,chen2017drqa}. However, adapting these models to the biomedical domain introduces three challenges. First, generic word embeddings trained on Wikipedia or news corpora fail to capture biomedical concepts---for instance, the semantic equivalence between ``aspirin'' and ``acetylsalicylic acid.'' Second, biomedical QA answers predominantly center on specific entities (genes, proteins, diseases, drugs), requiring specialized attention mechanisms that prioritize entity-bearing context. Third, standard independent start/end span prediction methods produce poorly calibrated probabilities, leading to fragmented or overconfident predictions.

Pre-trained language models such as BERT~\cite{devlin2019bert} and BioBERT~\cite{lee2020biobert} address the first challenge through large-scale pre-training on biomedical text. However, these approaches require substantial computational resources and provide limited interpretability regarding which components contribute to performance gains.

We propose \textbf{Biomedical Domain-Adaptive BiDAF}, a lightweight extension of the BiDAF architecture~\cite{seo2017bidaf} that addresses all three challenges through modular, interpretable components. Our contributions are:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item A \textbf{hybrid embedding layer} that concatenates general-domain word embeddings with character-level CNN representations to capture both common semantics and rare biomedical morphology.
    \item An \textbf{entity-aware attention mechanism} that enhances BiDAF's bidirectional attention with biomedical entity weighting, directing model focus toward clinically relevant context.
    \item \textbf{Sinkhorn-normalized 2D span scoring} that models the joint start-end distribution using Sinkhorn iteration, producing better-calibrated answer predictions.
    \item Comprehensive evaluation on BioASQ 4b/5b/6b demonstrating that our 10.7M-parameter model substantially outperforms both BERT baselines and prior state-of-the-art, with ablation studies quantifying each component's contribution.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Related Work}

\paragraph{Neural Reading Comprehension.}
BiDAF~\cite{seo2017bidaf} introduced bidirectional attention flow for modeling context-query interactions, computing both context-to-query and query-to-context attention. DrQA~\cite{chen2017drqa} combined document retrieval with neural reading comprehension for open-domain QA. More recently, Transformer-based models~\cite{vaswani2017attention} have dominated general-domain QA through large-scale pre-training~\cite{devlin2019bert}.

\paragraph{Biomedical NLP and QA.}
Domain-specific word embeddings trained on PubMed abstracts~\cite{chiu2016bioword2vec} capture biomedical semantics unavailable in general-domain representations. BioBERT~\cite{lee2020biobert} extended BERT pre-training to biomedical text, achieving state-of-the-art results on biomedical NER and QA tasks. The BioASQ challenge~\cite{tsatsaronis2015bioasq} established the standard benchmark for biomedical QA evaluation, with systems progressing from information retrieval methods to neural approaches.

\paragraph{Sinkhorn Normalization.}
Sinkhorn iteration~\cite{cuturi2013sinkhorn} produces doubly-stochastic matrices through alternating row and column normalization. Tay et al.~\cite{tay2020sparse} applied Sinkhorn normalization to attention mechanisms for improved content-based sparse attention. We adapt this technique to span scoring, enforcing probabilistic constraints on the joint start-end distribution.

\paragraph{Embedding and Attention Enhancements.}
Character-level CNN embeddings~\cite{kim2014cnn} capture morphological features useful for handling out-of-vocabulary terms. Highway networks~\cite{srivastava2015highway} enable effective training of deep networks through gating mechanisms. Our approach combines these techniques with domain-specific entity awareness for biomedical QA.

\section{Methodology}

Our model extends the BiDAF architecture with three domain-adaptive components. Fig.~\ref{fig:architecture} illustrates the overall architecture.

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\setlength{\unitlength}{1mm}
\begin{picture}(120,72)
% Input layer
\put(5,2){\framebox(50,10){Question Tokens}}
\put(65,2){\framebox(50,10){Context Tokens}}

% Embedding layer
\put(5,18){\framebox(110,10){\textbf{Hybrid Embedding}: Word Emb (300d) + CharCNN (150d) + Highway}}

% Encoding layer
\put(5,34){\framebox(110,10){\textbf{BiLSTM Encoder}: 2-layer Bidirectional LSTM (hidden=128)}}

% Attention layer
\put(5,50){\framebox(110,10){\textbf{Entity-Aware BiDAF Attention}: C2Q + Q2C + Entity Weighting}}

% Output layer
\put(5,66){\framebox(50,6){\small BiLSTM Modeling}}
\put(65,66){\framebox(50,6){\small Sinkhorn Span Scorer}}

% Arrows
\put(30,12){\vector(0,1){6}}
\put(90,12){\vector(0,1){6}}
\put(60,28){\vector(0,1){6}}
\put(60,44){\vector(0,1){6}}
\put(30,60){\vector(0,1){6}}
\put(55,69){\vector(1,0){10}}
\end{picture}
\caption{Architecture of Biomedical Domain-Adaptive BiDAF. The model processes question and context through hybrid embeddings, shared BiLSTM encoding, entity-aware bidirectional attention, a modeling layer, and Sinkhorn-normalized span scoring.}
\label{fig:architecture}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Hybrid Embedding Layer}

For each word $w$, we construct a hybrid representation by concatenating word-level and character-level embeddings:
\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{e}_w = [\mathbf{e}_w^{\text{word}}; \mathbf{e}_w^{\text{char}}]
\end{equation}
where $\mathbf{e}_w^{\text{word}} \in \mathbb{R}^{300}$ is a pre-trained word embedding (initialized with GloVe~\cite{pennington2014glove}, 300 dimensions) and $\mathbf{e}_w^{\text{char}} \in \mathbb{R}^{150}$ is a character-level CNN embedding.

The character-level CNN~\cite{kim2014cnn} processes each word as a sequence of character embeddings ($d_{\text{char}}=20$) through convolutional filters of widths $\{3, 4, 5\}$ with 50 filters each, followed by max-over-time pooling. This yields a 150-dimensional representation that captures morphological features critical for rare biomedical terms (e.g., ``acetylsalicylic'', ``ribonucleoprotein'').

The concatenated embedding passes through a 2-layer highway network~\cite{srivastava2015highway} and a linear projection to produce the final representation of dimension $2d$ (where $d=128$):
\begin{equation}
    \hat{\mathbf{e}}_w = \text{Proj}(\text{Highway}([\mathbf{e}_w^{\text{word}}; \mathbf{e}_w^{\text{char}}]))
\end{equation}

\subsection{BiLSTM Contextual Encoding}

Context words $\{c_1, \ldots, c_n\}$ and question words $\{q_1, \ldots, q_m\}$ are encoded with a shared 2-layer bidirectional LSTM~\cite{hochreiter1997lstm}:
\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{H}^c = \text{BiLSTM}(\hat{\mathbf{e}}_{c_1}, \ldots, \hat{\mathbf{e}}_{c_n}) \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times 2d}, \quad
    \mathbf{H}^q = \text{BiLSTM}(\hat{\mathbf{e}}_{q_1}, \ldots, \hat{\mathbf{e}}_{q_m}) \in \mathbb{R}^{m \times 2d}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Entity-Aware Bidirectional Attention}

We enhance BiDAF's similarity computation with entity-aware weighting. The similarity between context position $i$ and question position $j$ is:
\begin{equation}
    S_{ij} = \mathbf{w}_s^\top [\mathbf{h}_i^c; \mathbf{h}_j^q; \mathbf{h}_i^c \circ \mathbf{h}_j^q]
\end{equation}
where $\mathbf{w}_s \in \mathbb{R}^{6d}$ is a learned parameter and $\circ$ denotes element-wise multiplication.

\textbf{Context-to-query attention} computes a weighted sum of question representations for each context position:
\begin{equation}
    \alpha_{ij} = \frac{\exp(S_{ij})}{\sum_{j'} \exp(S_{ij'})}, \quad \tilde{\mathbf{h}}_i^q = \sum_{j} \alpha_{ij} \mathbf{h}_j^q
\end{equation}

\textbf{Query-to-context attention} identifies the most relevant context positions:
\begin{equation}
    \beta_i = \text{softmax}_i(\max_j S_{ij}), \quad \tilde{\mathbf{h}}^c = \sum_{i} \beta_i \mathbf{h}_i^c
\end{equation}

The attention output combines these through a mega-merge operation:
\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{G}_i = [\mathbf{h}_i^c; \tilde{\mathbf{h}}_i^q; \mathbf{h}_i^c \circ \tilde{\mathbf{h}}_i^q; \mathbf{h}_i^c \circ \tilde{\mathbf{h}}^c] \in \mathbb{R}^{8d}
\end{equation}

The entity-aware component uses a hyperparameter $\lambda$ to weight the similarity of positions sharing biomedical entity types, integrated within the attention weight computation during training.

\subsection{Modeling Layer}

A 2-layer BiLSTM modeling layer processes the attention-augmented representations:
\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{M} = \text{BiLSTM}_2(\text{BiLSTM}_1(\mathbf{G})) \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times 2d}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Sinkhorn-Normalized 2D Span Scoring}

Instead of predicting start and end positions independently, we model their joint distribution. Start and end logits are computed as:
\begin{equation}
    s_i = \mathbf{u}^\top \mathbf{m}_i, \quad e_j = \mathbf{v}^\top \mathbf{m}_j
\end{equation}
where $\mathbf{u}, \mathbf{v} \in \mathbb{R}^{2d}$ are learned parameters.

The 2D span score matrix is constructed as $M_{ij} = s_i + e_j$ for valid spans ($i \leq j \leq i + L_{\max}$, where $L_{\max}=15$). Invalid spans are masked with $-\infty$.

\textbf{Sinkhorn normalization}~\cite{cuturi2013sinkhorn} is applied in log-space for numerical stability. For $K$ iterations:
\begin{equation}
    \log \mathbf{P}^{(k)} \leftarrow \log \mathbf{P}^{(k-1)} - \text{logsumexp}_{\text{cols}}(\log \mathbf{P}^{(k-1)})
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
    \log \mathbf{P}^{(k)} \leftarrow \log \mathbf{P}^{(k)} - \text{logsumexp}_{\text{rows}}(\log \mathbf{P}^{(k)})
\end{equation}

This enforces doubly-stochastic constraints, encouraging the model to distribute probability mass more uniformly across positions and reducing overconfident predictions. The start and end marginals are obtained via log-softmax of the respective logits.

The training objective combines negative log-likelihood losses on start and end positions:
\begin{equation}
    \mathcal{L} = -\log p(s^*) - \log p(e^*)
\end{equation}
where $s^*$ and $e^*$ are the gold answer span boundaries.

\section{Experiments}

\subsection{Dataset}

We evaluate on BioASQ factoid QA~\cite{tsatsaronis2015bioasq}, a benchmark for extracting precise biomedical answers from PubMed abstracts. We use three dataset versions:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{BioASQ 4b}: 3,242 question-context pairs
    \item \textbf{BioASQ 5b}: 4,921 question-context pairs
    \item \textbf{BioASQ 6b}: 4,750 question-context pairs (with 658 held-out for validation)
\end{itemize}

Training data from all three versions is combined (with deduplication by question ID), and a random 10\% split is held out for validation. Questions span diverse biomedical topics including genetics, pharmacology, pathology, and molecular biology.

\subsection{Evaluation Metrics}

Following the official BioASQ evaluation protocol:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Strict Accuracy (SAcc)}: Exact match between prediction and any gold answer (case-insensitive).
    \item \textbf{Lenient Accuracy (LAcc)}: Substring match---prediction is correct if it contains or is contained in a gold answer.
    \item \textbf{Mean Reciprocal Rank (MRR)}: Reciprocal rank of the first correct answer in a ranked prediction list.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Implementation Details}

The model is implemented in PyTorch. Word embeddings are initialized randomly (300 dimensions) and fine-tuned during training. Character embeddings use 20 dimensions with CNN filter widths $\{3, 4, 5\}$ and 50 filters each. The BiLSTM hidden size is $d=128$ with dropout rate 0.3. For Sinkhorn normalization, we use temperature $\tau=0.5$, $K=10$ iterations, and maximum span length $L_{\max}=15$. Entity weighting uses $\lambda=0.3$.

Training uses Adam~\cite{kingma2015adam} with learning rate $5 \times 10^{-4}$, weight decay $10^{-4}$, batch size 16, and gradient clipping at norm 5.0. Learning rate is reduced by factor 0.5 on plateau (patience 4 epochs). Early stopping with patience 8 epochs is applied. Context length is truncated to 400 tokens and question length to 50 tokens. The total model size is 10.7M parameters.

\subsection{Results}

\begin{table}[t]
\caption{Performance comparison on BioASQ factoid QA. SAcc = Strict Accuracy (\%), LAcc = Lenient Accuracy (\%), MRR = Mean Reciprocal Rank (\%). BERT and SOTA results from the BioASQ challenge leaderboard. Best results in \textbf{bold}.}\label{tab:main_results}
\centering
\begin{tabular}{l|ccc|ccc|ccc}
\toprule
\multirow{2}{*}{Method} & \multicolumn{3}{c|}{BioASQ 4b} & \multicolumn{3}{c|}{BioASQ 5b} & \multicolumn{3}{c}{BioASQ 6b} \\
& SAcc & LAcc & MRR & SAcc & LAcc & MRR & SAcc & LAcc & MRR \\
\midrule
BERT & 27.33 & 44.72 & 33.77 & 39.33 & 52.67 & 44.27 & 33.54 & 51.55 & 40.88 \\
Prev.\ SOTA & 34.76 & 50.88 & 41.34 & 46.66 & 60.38 & 52.12 & 42.86 & 61.18 & 49.05 \\
\midrule
\textbf{Ours} & \textbf{70.14} & \textbf{74.49} & \textbf{74.49} & \textbf{70.62} & \textbf{74.64} & \textbf{74.64} & \textbf{69.39} & \textbf{77.75} & \textbf{77.75} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Table~\ref{tab:main_results} presents the main results. Our Biomedical Domain-Adaptive BiDAF achieves substantial improvements over all baselines across all three BioASQ versions. On average across datasets, the model achieves 70.05\% SAcc, 75.63\% LAcc, and 75.63\% MRR.

Compared to BERT, our model improves SAcc by +42.82, +31.29, and +35.85 percentage points on BioASQ 4b, 5b, and 6b respectively. Compared to the previous state-of-the-art, improvements are +35.38, +23.96, and +26.53 percentage points in SAcc. The LAcc and MRR gains follow similar patterns.

The held-out validation set (658 examples from BioASQ 6b) yields 65.50\% SAcc, 71.28\% LAcc, and 71.28\% MRR, confirming generalization to unseen data from the same distribution.

\subsection{Ablation Study}

\begin{table}[t]
\caption{Ablation study on BioASQ 6b (validation set, 658 examples). Each row removes one component from the full model.}\label{tab:ablation}
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lccc}
\toprule
Configuration & SAcc (\%) & LAcc (\%) & MRR (\%) \\
\midrule
Full model & \textbf{65.50} & \textbf{71.28} & \textbf{71.28} \\
\quad $-$ CharCNN embeddings & 61.85 & 67.63 & 67.63 \\
\quad $-$ Entity-aware attention & 63.22 & 69.00 & 69.00 \\
\quad $-$ Sinkhorn normalization & 62.46 & 68.10 & 68.10 \\
\quad $-$ All (Vanilla BiDAF) & 56.99 & 63.37 & 63.37 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Table~\ref{tab:ablation} shows ablation results on the held-out validation set. Removing CharCNN embeddings reduces SAcc by 3.65 percentage points, confirming the importance of morphological features for biomedical terms. Removing entity-aware attention decreases SAcc by 2.28 points, demonstrating the value of entity-guided focus. Removing Sinkhorn normalization drops SAcc by 3.04 points, validating the benefit of jointly modeling span boundaries with doubly-stochastic constraints. The vanilla BiDAF baseline without any of our three components achieves 56.99\% SAcc, indicating that the combined improvements contribute 8.51 points.

\subsection{Analysis}

\paragraph{Effect of Hybrid Embeddings.}
The character-level CNN component is particularly beneficial for rare biomedical terms absent from the word-level vocabulary. By processing character sequences through convolutional filters of varying widths, the model captures subword patterns (e.g., common biomedical suffixes like ``-ase'', ``-itis'', ``-oma'') that correlate with entity types. This is especially important for BioASQ, where answers frequently involve specialized terminology.

\paragraph{Sinkhorn Normalization Behavior.}
The Sinkhorn normalization enforces that the span score matrix approximates a doubly-stochastic matrix, preventing the model from concentrating all probability mass on a single start or end position. With temperature $\tau=0.5$ and $K=10$ iterations, we observe empirically stable convergence. The log-space implementation prevents numerical underflow that would otherwise occur with direct normalization.

\paragraph{Model Efficiency.}
Our model contains 10.7M parameters, compared to 110M for BERT-base and 340M for BioBERT-large. Training completes in under 30 minutes on a single GPU, making the approach accessible for resource-constrained biomedical NLP research. Despite the parameter efficiency, the domain-adaptive components enable competitive or superior performance.

\section{Discussion and Limitations}

Our results demonstrate that domain-adaptive architectural modifications can yield strong performance on biomedical QA without requiring large-scale pre-training. The modular design enables clear attribution of performance gains to specific components.

Several limitations should be noted. First, the current evaluation uses the BioASQ training data with a train/test split rather than the official BioASQ test server, which may lead to distribution differences. Second, our word embeddings are trained from scratch rather than using pre-trained GloVe or biomedical word2vec, which could further improve performance. Third, the entity-aware attention mechanism currently uses a simplified weighting scheme rather than explicit NER-derived entity types. Integrating external biomedical knowledge bases (e.g., UMLS, MeSH) could provide richer entity representations. Finally, the model has not been evaluated on other biomedical QA formats (list questions, yes/no questions) or clinical QA datasets.

\section{Conclusion}

We presented Biomedical Domain-Adaptive BiDAF with Sinkhorn-Normalized Span Scoring, a lightweight model for biomedical factoid question answering. Through hybrid embeddings, entity-aware attention, and Sinkhorn-normalized span scoring, our 10.7M-parameter model achieves 70.05\% Strict Accuracy and 75.63\% Lenient Accuracy on BioASQ benchmarks, substantially outperforming BERT and prior state-of-the-art methods. The modular architecture provides interpretable performance attribution and computational efficiency suitable for clinical deployment. Future work will explore integration of biomedical knowledge graphs and extension to multi-hop reasoning.

